Setup Transactional Replication between two AWS EC2 SQL Server Instances on different domains:
--https://share.google/aimode/nOCrshgvqstXccX42

To set up transactional replication between two AWS EC2 SQL Server instances in different domains, you must address two primary challenges: 
network connectivity and authentication between untrusted domains.

*******************************
1. Network & Connectivity Setup
*******************************
Replication requires the Publisher and Subscriber to communicate over specific ports.

* Security Groups: Update the [AWS EC2 Security Groups](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/database/native-sql-server-replication-options-on-amazon-rds-custom-for-sql-server/) 
  for both instances to allow inbound traffic on Port 1433 (SQL Server).

* Name Resolution: Because the instances are in different domains, they may not resolve each other's hostnames. 
 Manually add entries to the Windows hosts file (C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts) on both servers, mapping the private IP addresses to the SQL Server instance names. [2, 3, 4] 

*******************************
2. Authentication Strategy
*******************************
Since the domains do not trust each other, you have two main options:

* SQL Server Authentication: This is often the simplest approach for cross-domain setups. 
You must use a dedicated SQL login with sysadmin privileges on both instances to run the replication agents.

* Mirroring Local Accounts: Create identical local Windows users (same username and password) on both EC2 instances. 
Grant these accounts sysadmin rights in SQL Server and permissions to the Snapshot Folder. This mimics a trusted environment for the replication agents.

*******************************
3. Configuration Steps
*******************************
Follow these steps in SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS):

   1. Configure Distribution:
   * Right-click the Replication folder on the Publisher and select Configure Distribution.
      * Set up a Snapshot Folder. If using a network share, ensure both the Publisher and Subscriber service accounts have read/write access to it.
   2. Create Publication:
   * Right-click Local Publications > New Publication.
      * Select the source database and choose Transactional publication.
      * Select the tables to replicate (they must have Primary Keys).
   3. Create Subscription:
   * Right-click the new publication and select New Subscriptions.
      * Choose between a Push (Distributor pushes data) or Pull (Subscriber pulls data) subscription.
      * In the Agent Security step, specify the SQL Server login or the mirrored local Windows account you created earlier.
   4. Initialize:
   * Allow the Snapshot Agent to generate the initial schema and data files. 
Once complete, the Distribution Agent will apply them to the Subscriber to start the synchronization. 

