T-SQL script template to automate the creation of the publication and subscription for this cross-domain environment:
--https://share.google/aimode/8bzE1aPzOUHTYGOMQ

Setting up replication between EC2 instances in different domains requires scripts that use SQL Server Authentication or local "mirrored" accounts, as standard domain authentication will fail. 

**************************************************
Step 1: Configure Distribution (On Publisher)
**************************************************
Run this on the Publisher instance to set itself up as the Distributor. Replace 'DistributorPassword' with a strong password. 

-- Connect to the Publisher
USE master;
EXEC sp_adddistributor 
@distributor = @@SERVERNAME, 
@password = N'DistributorPassword';

-- Create the distribution database
EXEC sp_adddistributiondb 
@database = N'distribution', 
@security_mode = 1; -- 1 = Windows Auth for the local agent

-- Enable the Publisher to use this Distributor
EXEC sp_adddistpublisher 
    @publisher = @@SERVERNAME, 
    @distribution_db = N'distribution', 
    @security_mode = 1, 
    @working_directory = N'\\Your-EC2-IP\ReplSnapshot'; -- Use a UNC path accessible by both
GO

**************************************************
Step 2: Create Publication (On Publisher)
**************************************************
Enable the database for replication and add the tables (articles).

USE [YourDatabaseName];-- Enable replication for this DB
EXEC sp_replicationdboption 
@dbname = N'YourDatabaseName', 
@optname = N'publish', 
@value = N'true';

-- Add the publication
EXEC sp_addpublication 
    @publication = N'CrossDomainPub', 
    @repl_freq = N'continuous',
    @status = N'active', 
    @independent_agent = N'true';

-- Add the Snapshot Agent (using a local mirrored account or SQL login)
EXEC sp_addpublication_snapshot 
   @publication = N'CrossDomainPub', 
    @frequency_type = 1, 
    @publisher_security_mode = 0, -- 0 = SQL Server Authentication
    @publisher_login = N'ReplicationUser', 
    @publisher_password = N'StrongPassword';

-- Add a specific table as an article
EXEC sp_addarticle 
    @publication = N'CrossDomainPub', 
    @article = N'YourTableName', 
    @source_object = N'YourTableName', 
    @destination_table = N'YourTableName', 
    @type = N'logbased';
GO

**************************************************
Step 3: Create Push Subscription (On Publisher)
**************************************************
This script defines the Subscriber server. 
Since it is cross-domain, you must explicitly use a [SQL Server login]
(https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/database/native-sql-server-replication-options-on-amazon-rds-custom-for-sql-server/) for the connection to the Subscriber.

USE [YourDatabaseName];
-- Add the subscription metadata
EXEC sp_addsubscription 
    @publication = N'CrossDomainPub', 
    @subscriber = N'Subscriber-EC2-Hostname', -- Must be resolvable via hosts file
    @destination_db = N'SubscriberDBName', 
    @subscription_type = N'Push';

-- Configure the Distribution Agent to use SQL Authentication for the Subscriber
EXEC sp_addpushsubscription_agent 
    @publication = N'CrossDomainPub', 
    @subscriber = N'Subscriber-EC2-Hostname', 
    @subscriber_db = N'SubscriberDBName', 
    @subscriber_security_mode = 0, -- 0 = SQL Authentication
    @subscriber_login = N'ReplicationUser', 
    @subscriber_password = N'StrongPassword',
    @job_login = null, 
    @job_password = null; -- Agent runs under SQL Agent account
GO

Critical Verification Checklist
**Hostnames: Ensure Subscriber-EC2-Hostname in the script matches the entry in your C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts file.
**Snapshot Share: The @working_directory must be a folder shared via Windows (SMB) where the Subscriber’s service account has Read access and the Publisher has Write access.
**Permissions: The ReplicationUser must be a member of the db_owner role on both the publication and subscription databases.
* Snapshot Share: The @working_directory must be a folder shared via Windows (SMB) where the Subscriber’s service account has Read access and the Publisher has Write access.
* Permissions: The ReplicationUser must be a member of the db_owner role on both the publication and subscription databases.

************************************************************************************************************************************
Verify the Snapshot Agent status to ensure the initial data transfer has started
************************************************************************************************************************************
To verify the Snapshot Agent status and ensure your initial data transfer is proceeding correctly, you can use either the Graphical User Interface (SSMS) or a T-SQL query on the Distributor.

Option 1: Using SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS)
===========================================
This is the most intuitive method for a quick visual check. 
   1. Connect to the Publisher instance in SSMS.
   2. Expand the Replication folder, then expand Local Publications.
   3. Right-click your publication (e.g., CrossDomainPub) and select View Snapshot Agent Status.
   4. In the dialog box, you will see the current status (e.g., "Starting", "In progress", or "Completed").
   * If it hasn't started, click Start to manually trigger the snapshot generation.
      * Check the Message area for details like "Bulk copying data into table...". [1, 4, 5, 6, 7] 
   
Option 2: Using T-SQL (On the Distributor)
===========================================
If you prefer scripting or need to check from a command line, run the following query on the server acting as the Distributor (usually your Publisher in this setup).

USE distribution;
GO
SELECT 
    p.publication AS [Publication Name],
    s.agent_name AS [Agent Name],
    CASE s.status
        WHEN 1 THEN 'Started'
        WHEN 2 THEN 'Succeeded'
        WHEN 3 THEN 'In progress'
        WHEN 4 THEN 'Idle'
        WHEN 5 THEN 'Retrying'
        WHEN 6 THEN 'Failed'
    END AS [Status],
    s.start_time AS [Start Time],
    s.comments AS [Last Message]FROM dbo.MSsnapshot_history sJOIN dbo.MSsnapshot_agents p ON s.agent_id = p.idWHERE s.timestamp = (
    SELECT MAX(timestamp) 
    FROM dbo.MSsnapshot_history 
    WHERE agent_id = p.id
)ORDER BY p.publication;

What to Look For:
=================
* "Completed" Status: Once the Snapshot Agent finishes, it creates the schema and data files in your Snapshot Folder. Replication will not begin moving data until this status is achieved.
* Distribution Agent: After the snapshot is ready, you must also check the Distribution Agent (via Replication Monitor) to ensure it is successfully applying those files to the Subscriber.
* Agent Errors: If the status shows "Failed," check the Error details in SSMS. 
Common cross-domain issues include Access Denied on the snapshot folder share or Login Failed for the subscriber account.


**********************************************************************************************************
How to troubleshoot the "Access Denied" error if the Snapshot Agent fails to write to your AWS file share
**********************************************************************************************************
In a cross-domain EC2 setup, "Access Denied" usually happens because the SQL Server Agent service on the Publisher cannot write to the folder, or the Subscriber cannot read from it.

Follow these steps to resolve permissions for the Snapshot Folder:

1. Match the Local Service Accounts
Since there is no domain trust, you must use "Mirrored" local accounts.

* Create an identical user (e.g., .\ReplUser) on both EC2 instances.
* Use the exact same password for both.
* Go to services.msc and set the SQL Server Agent service to "Log On As" this new ReplUser.

2. Configure the Windows Folder Share
On the instance hosting the snapshot folder (usually the Publisher):

* Right-click folder > Properties > Sharing > Advanced Sharing:
* Check "Share this folder."
* Click Permissions and add the local ReplUser. Grant Full Control.
* Properties > Security tab (NTFS):
* Add the local ReplUser. Grant Modify or Full Control.

3. Use the UNC Path (Not a Drive Letter)
In your replication scripts or SSMS wizard, never use C:\ReplData. 
You must use the Universal Naming Convention (UNC) path so the Subscriber can find it over the network:

* Correct: \\Publisher-Private-IP\ReplSnapshot
* Incorrect: C:\ReplSnapshot

4. Test Connectivity via File Explorer
To confirm the "bridge" is working:

   1. Log into the Subscriber EC2 as ReplUser.
   2. Open File Explorer and paste the UNC path (e.g., \\10.0.x.x\ReplSnapshot) into the address bar.
   3. If you can create a new text file in that folder from the Subscriber, the "Access Denied" error will disappear.

5. Update the SQL Agent Job
If you already tried to start the agent and it failed, the login might be cached.

* Open SQL Server Agent > Jobs.
* Find the Snapshot Agent job (it will have a long name like Publisher-DB-Pub-1).
* Right-click > Properties > Steps > Edit.
* Ensure the command uses the -PublisherSecurityMode 0 (SQL Auth) if you are passing credentials through the command line.

***************************************************************************************************************************
PowerShell commands to quickly create these local users and set folder permissions across both servers
***************************************************************************************************************************
To automate the setup of mirrored accounts and the snapshot folder share across your EC2 instances, you can use these 
[PowerShell](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.localaccounts/new-localuser?view=powershell-5.1) scripts.

1. Create Mirrored Local User
Run this script on both the Publisher and Subscriber EC2 instances. Ensure the password matches exactly on both servers to allow the cross-domain "handshake". [1, 2] 

# Run on BOTH Publisher and Subscriber EC2s
$Username = "ReplUser"
$Password = ConvertTo-SecureString "YourStrongPassword!123" -AsPlainText -Force
# Create the Local User
New-LocalUser -Name $Username -Password $Password -Description "SQL Replication Mirrored Account" -PasswordNeverExpires $true
# Add to Local Administrators (Optional but recommended for SQL Agent permissions)
Add-LocalGroupMember -Group "Administrators" -Member $Username

2. Configure Snapshot Folder and Share
Run this script on the Publisher EC2. It creates the folder, applies the necessary NTFS permissions, and creates the 
[SMB network share](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/smbshare/new-smbshare?view=windowsserver2025-ps). [3, 4, 5] 

# Run on the PUBLISHER EC2 only
$Path = "C:\ReplSnapshot"
$Username = "ReplUser"
# 1. Create Folder if it doesn't existif (!(Test-Path $Path)) { New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path $Path }
# 2. Set NTFS Permissions (Modify access for the replication account)
$Acl = Get-Acl $Path
$Ar = New-Object System.Security.AccessControl.FileSystemAccessRule($Username, "Modify", "ContainerInherit,ObjectInherit", "None", "Allow")
$Acl.SetAccessRule($Ar)
Set-Acl $Path $Acl
# 3. Create SMB Share for the Subscriber to access
New-SmbShare -Name "ReplSnapshot" -Path $Path -FullAccess $Username

3. Verification Commands
After running the scripts, you can verify the setup from the Subscriber EC2 to ensure the cross-domain access is working:

* Test Network Path: Open PowerShell on the Subscriber and run Test-Path "\\Publisher-Private-IP\ReplSnapshot". It should return True.
* Check Shared Folders: Run Get-SmbShare -Name "ReplSnapshot" on the Publisher to confirm the share is active. [4] 

Next Steps:
Once these permissions are set, you can restart the SQL Server Agent on both servers using the ReplUser account. 

********************************************************************
Commands for re-pointing the SQL Agent service to this new account:
********************************************************************
To re-point the SQL Server Agent service to your new mirrored account, you can use WMI (Windows Management Instrumentation) via PowerShell. 
This method is preferred over standard Set-Service commands because it correctly updates the service's internal 
[security identifiers (SIDs)](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/database-engine/configure-windows/scm-services-change-the-service-startup-account?view=sql-server-ver17) and permissions required by SQL Server. [1, 2, 3] 

PowerShell Command to Update Service Account:
=============================================
Run this on both the Publisher and Subscriber instances. 
Replace YourStrongPassword!123 with the password you set in the previous step.

# Specify the service name (standard instance is 'SQLSERVERAGENT')
$ServiceName = "SQLSERVERAGENT"
$NewUser = ".\ReplUser"
$NewPassword = "YourStrongPassword!123"
# Retrieve the service via WMI
$Service = Get-WmiObject Win32_Service | Where-Object { $_.Name -eq $ServiceName }
# Change the Logon account and password# Parameters: Name, DisplayName, PathName, ServiceType, ErrorControl, StartMode, DesktopInteract, StartName, StartPassword...
$Result = $Service.Change($null, $null, $null, $null, $null, $null, $NewUser, $NewPassword, $null, $null, $null)
# Verify the result (0 = Success)if ($Result.ReturnValue -eq 0) {
    Write-Host "Successfully updated $ServiceName to log on as $NewUser" -ForegroundColor Green
    Restart-Service $ServiceName -Force
    Write-Host "Service restarted." -ForegroundColor Cyan
} else {
    Write-Host "Failed to update service. Error code: $($Result.ReturnValue)" -ForegroundColor Red
}

Important Execution Details:
============================
* Run as Administrator: You must launch the PowerShell console with Elevated Privileges for the Change method to work.
* Service Name: If you are using a Named Instance (e.g., EC2AMAZ-ABC\SQL2019), the service name will be SQLAgent$SQL2019. You can find the exact name by running Get-Service *SQLAGENT*.
* Downtime: Changing the service account [requires a restart](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=30pw4O_hBvg) of the SQL Server Agent service. Existing replication jobs will pause briefly during this window.
* Permissions: The Change method automatically grants the "Log on as a service" right to the new account on the local machine. [4, 5, 6] 

Post-Change Verification
After running the command, open SQL Server Configuration Manager or services.msc to confirm the "Log On As" column now shows .\ReplUser.

************************************************************************************************************************
How to configure the SQL Server Logins for this account so it has the necessary sysadmin rights to manage replication?
************************************************************************************************************************
To allow the replication agent to function across untrusted domains, the local [mirrored account]
(https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19730218/setup-replication-on-two-database-on-different-domain) must be granted administrative access within SQL Server on both the Publisher and Subscriber instances,

SQL Server Permission Requirements
Replication tasks typically require the following [security roles](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/relational-databases/replication/security/security-role-requirements-for-replication?view=sql-server-ver17): [2] 

* sysadmin: Required on the Publisher to enable databases and manage the Distributor.
* db_owner: Required on the distribution database and the specific publication or subscription database for the agent account to operate.

T-SQL Configuration Script:
===========================
Run this script in SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS) on both the Publisher and Subscriber. 
It creates the login for your local Windows user and grants it the necessary sysadmin role to bypass individual database permission hurdles.

-- Replace 'YourServerName' with the actual local hostname of the EC2
-- Replace 'ReplUser' with the mirrored account name you created earlier

USE [master];
GO
-- 1. Create a SQL login from the local Windows accountCREATE LOGIN [YourServerName\ReplUser] FROM WINDOWS;
GO
-- 2. Grant the sysadmin server role-- For SQL Server 2012 and newer:ALTER SERVER ROLE [sysadmin] ADD MEMBER [YourServerName\ReplUser];
GO
-- For older versions (pre-2012):
-- EXEC sp_addsrvrolemember 'YourServerName\ReplUser', 'sysadmin';-- GO

Alternative: Least Privilege (Recommended for Production)
If you prefer not to grant full sysadmin rights for security reasons, you must explicitly map the user to the following:

   1. On Publisher: Add to db_owner on the publication database and the distribution database.
   2. On Subscriber: Add to db_owner on the subscription database.
   3. Publication Access List (PAL): Ensure the login is added to the [PAL](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/relational-databases/replication/security/secure-the-publisher?view=sql-server-ver17) of your publication. [3, 4, 7] 

Next Steps:
Once the permissions are in place, you are ready to start the Snapshot Agent. 

