How to monitor Replication Monitor for real-time performance and error tracking?
*******************************************************************************

To monitor your cross-domain transactional replication in real-time, use SQL Server Replication Monitor in SSMS. 
This tool is essential for identifying whether performance bottlenecks or errors are occurring at the Publisher, Distributor, or Subscriber. 
1. Launching Replication Monitor

* Connect to your Publisher instance in SSMS.
* Right-click the Replication folder and select Launch Replication Monitor.
* Expand the Publisher in the left pane to see your specific publications.

2. Tracking Real-Time Performance (Tracer Tokens)
The most effective way to measure cross-domain latency (which can be higher due to network hops between AWS VPCs or regions) is by using Tracer Tokens.

* In Replication Monitor, select your publication and go to the Tracer Tokens tab.
* Click Insert Tracer. This sends a tiny "heartbeat" transaction through the system.
* Monitor the three latency columns:
* Publisher to Distributor: Time taken for the Log Reader Agent to move data from the transaction log to the distribution database.
   * Distributor to Subscriber: Time taken for the Distribution Agent to move data from the Distributor to your secondary EC2.
   * Total Latency: The end-to-end delay. 

3. Pinpointing Errors by Agent
If replication stops, Replication Monitor will show a red "X". Use the All Subscriptions tab to find the failing agent: 

* Log Reader Agent Error: The issue is between the Publisher and Distributor. Often caused by high transaction volume or disk I/O on the Publisher.
* Distribution Agent Error: The issue is between the Distributor and Subscriber. 
In cross-domain setups, this is typically a network timeout or permission error (Access Denied) when trying to connect to the remote Subscriber. 

4. Advanced Troubleshooting

* View Details: Right-click a subscription and select View Details to see a chronological history of agent messages.
* Undistributed Commands: Check the Distributor to Subscriber History tab to see how many commands are waiting in the distribution database. 
  A high number indicates the Subscriber cannot keep up.
* Validation: You can right-click a subscription and select Validate Subscription to ensure the row counts on the Publisher and Subscriber match. 

*****************************************************************************************************************
T-SQL query to check for "undistributed commands" directly from the distribution database without using the UI?
*****************************************************************************************************************
To check for replication lag and "undistributed commands" (commands that have reached the Distributor but haven't been applied to the Subscriber yet) without using the UI, 
run this query on the Distributor (usually your Publisher EC2).

T-SQL: Check Undistributed Command Count
This query identifies which subscriptions are falling behind and exactly how many transactions are waiting in the queue.

USE [distribution];
GO
SELECT 
    s.name AS [Subscriber],
    su.publisher_db AS [PublisherDB],
    su.publication AS [Publication],
    SUM(count_diff) AS [Undistributed_Command_Count],
    -- Estimates time to catch up based on current agent speed
    MAX(delivery_rate) AS [Current_Delivery_Rate_Cmds_Per_Sec]FROM dbo.MSdistribution_status dsJOIN dbo.MSdistribution_agents s ON ds.agent_id = s.idJOIN dbo.MSsubscriptions su ON s.subscriber_id = su.subscriber_idGROUP BY s.name, su.publisher_db, su.publication;
GO

T-SQL: View Detailed Agent Latency
If you want to see the specific latency (in seconds) for the last run of the Distribution Agent, use this query:

USE [distribution];
GO
SELECT 
    publication AS [Publication],
    subscriber_db AS [SubscriberDB],
    CASE status 
        WHEN 1 THEN 'Started'
        WHEN 2 THEN 'Succeeded'
        WHEN 3 THEN 'In progress'
        WHEN 4 THEN 'Idle'
        WHEN 5 THEN 'Retrying'
        WHEN 6 THEN 'Failed'
    END AS [AgentStatus],
    delivery_latency / 1000 AS [Latency_Seconds], -- Converted from ms
    last_run_getdate AS [LastSyncTime]FROM dbo.MSdistribution_historyWHERE id IN (SELECT MAX(id) FROM dbo.MSdistribution_history GROUP BY agent_id)ORDER BY last_run_getdate DESC;

   1. Network Latency: High latency between AWS VPCs can slow down the acknowledgment of each batch of commands.
   2. Batch Size: The default -CommitBatchSize (100) might be too small for high-volume cross-domain traffic.
   3. Permissions: If the ReplUser password was changed on one node but not the other, the agent will go into a "Retrying" state, increasing the undistributed count.
